topic.title: Clocking Architecture

body.p: Reference clocks (both input and output) are arranged based around a PCIe Stack (x16 lanes wide). Some stacks have a single clock synthesis unit shared between the two stacks. Other stacks have a dedicated CSU per stack.

Each CSU is capable of receiving up to 4 input clocks to the ports within the stack. It is important to note that not ALL host input clocks are routed to every stack. The diagrams below will illustrate the limitations.

note.p: The ports in Stack 6 are only available in Revision B of the switch.
For Switchtec variants that do not contain specific stacks (where stack 2 or 3 are not used), the corresponding CSUs are also unavailable

section.title: Clocking CSU Architecture
section.p: Each CSU in Switchtec is comprised of some multiplexers which provide the ability for individual ports in the switch to use different clocking schemes.
In #Clocking_Architecture/fig_External_reference_clock_to_CSU_channel__1ig015tga the CSU that controls stack 0 and 1 is illustrated. The inputs to this CSU are:

The CSU itself provides 3 channels of clock to the port. This means from the 4 input clocks provided to the CSU, three of them can be used to clock ports within stacks 0 and 1. This provides up to three clocking variants for all ports using stacks 0 and 1. One example use-case of picking three clocking options for the CSU is:

note.p: For SRIS applications, CSU Channel 1 is dedicated for this operation. Ports using SRIS must use CSU Channel 1 and the reference clock input for CSU Channel 1 MUST be a non-SSC clock input to the switch. PCIE_REFCLK_D is, by default, a non-SSC clock and is a good candidate for this use-case.
If SRIS is not used, CSU Channel 1 can be used like any other CSU Channel.

section.p: The configuration in Switchtec allows for a high level of flexibility with which input clock can be used to source a CSU channel. For example, PCIE_REFCLK_H0 could be used to feed CSU Channel 0 which enables SSC to provide Common SSC to ports using CSU Channel 0. At the same time, PCIE_REFCLK_H0 can also be used to clock CSU Channel 1 which disables SSC to provide Common noSSC to other ports in stacks 0 and 1.
Output clocks are derived from the Channel CSUs and will have SSC or no SSC dependent on their configuration.
